Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting entry to effect the share 15% and 5% share of the OBO and DPWH, respectively from the collection of building permit;
Municipal Treasurer strictly monitor the amount to be automatically retained with the Municipal to be used for OBO’s programs and projects and the amount to be remitted to BTr representing the 5%share of DPWH; and
Municipal Engineering Office as the OBO to prepare Program of Work detailing the manner on the utilization of the 15% share from the collection of building permits, and properly observe the guidelines in the preparation of the program of works.

We have recommended that the local government unit strictly adhere with the existing laws, rules and regulations covering the appropriation and utilization of the 20% Local Development Fund to avoid possible sanctions that may be imposed for non-compliance. Further, we recommend the following:

a.	 That the 20% Local Development Fund be optimally utilize in order to deliver the benefits of desirable social, economic and environmental outcomes to the constituents which is essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all; 

That the Local Chief Executive ensure that the employees concerned faithfully supervise and monitor the construction activities, including but not limited to the inspection of works to ensure that the construction is completed within the plan and timeframe in order to deliver the essential benefits of the projects to the constituents.

We have recommended that the local government unit strictly adhere with the existing laws, rules and regulations covering the appropriation and utilization of the 20% Local Development Fund to avoid possible sanctions that may be imposed for non-compliance. Further, we recommend the following:
That the 20% Local Development Fund be optimally utilize in order to deliver the benefits of desirable social, economic and environmental outcomes to the constituents which is essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all;
That the Local Chief Executive ensure that the employees concerned faithfully supervise and monitor the construction activities, including but not limited to the inspection of works to ensure that the construction is completed within the plan and timeframe in order to deliver the essential benefits of the projects to the constituents.

We have recommended the following measured to the management – 

Strictly use the local fund for its specified purpose as authorized in the appropriation ordinance/ approved budget or seek the authorization of the local sanggunian for the transfer of budget allocated for an approved project/program/activity to another project/program/activity in compliance with Section 305 of RA 7160 and in order to avoid disallowance in audit;
Submit a copy of a resolution or an ordinance authorization the Local Chief Executive to grant loans to the small scaled business persons in the Villasis Market;
 Utilize only bonded collectors to undertake the collection of loan repayments to provide the LGU adequate safeguard for possible theft or loss of funds;
Instruct the personnel assigned in the collection of load repayments and/or Accounting Department to maintain a subsidiary ledger card in order to have a detailed record on the release of load and collection of loan repayments as well as the outstanding loan balance of each borrower or loanee as of the reporting date or cut-off date as the case may be;

Require prompt issuance of official receipt to acknowledge receipt of loan repayments in compliance with Section 68 of PD 1445.

We have recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee strictly adhere with all provisions of laws, rules and regulations pertaining to procurements to protect the interest of the local government unit at all times. We have further recommended that –
Invitation to Bid/Request for Expression of Interest be posted continuously in the PhilGEPS website for seven (7) calendar days starting on date of advertisement;
Pre-bid conference be held at least twelve (12) calendar days before the deadline for the submission and receipt of bids, but not earlier than seven (7) calendar days from the PhilGEPS posting of the Invitation to Bid or Bidding Documents;
The maximum periods and the recommended earliest possible time for action on specific procurement activities as provided in Section 38.2 and Annex “C” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 be strictly observed in all of the procurement transactions of the local government unit;
The Notice of Award be issued within fifteen (15) calendar days from the determination by the BAC of the bidder with the LCRB and recommendation to award the contract in compliance with Section 37.1.2 of 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Republic Act (RA) 9184;
The APP be submitted to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year and be posted in accordance with E.O. 662, series of 2007, as amended;
Observer from duly recognized private group be invited in all stages of procurement, for example in the procurement of goods, a specific relevant chamber-member of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry and national associations of contractors duly recognized by the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines (CIAP) for infrastructure projects;
The Notices of Award and Notices to Proceed and the approved contract of   projects awarded be posted in the agency website;
The schedule of delivery be specified in the Schedule of Requirements form and Purchase Order in order to provide reckoning date for the computation of liquidated damages, if any; and
The supporting documents being required in item No. 9 be submitted for further evaluation of Audit Team and in order to avoid suspension in audit.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that –
The Bids and Awards Committee explain in writing why the Bid of Megabullseye Corporation was not disqualified despite of its failure to indicate the bid offer in the Financial Bid Form;
The APP be submitted to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year and be posted in accordance with E.O. 662, series of 2007, as amended;
Observer from duly recognized private group be invited in all stages of procurement, for example in the procurement of goods, a specific relevant chamber-member of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry and national associations of contractors duly recognized by the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines (CIAP) for infrastructure projects to enhance transparency;
The Notices of Award and Notices to Proceed and the approved contract of projects awarded be posted in the agency website;
The supporting documents being required in item No. 5 be submitted for further evaluation of Audit Team and in order to avoid suspension in audit; and
The Notice of Award be issued within fifteen (15) calendar days from the determination by the BAC of the bidder with the LCRB and recommendation to award the contract in compliance with Section 37.1.2 of 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of Republic Act (RA) 9184.
We have further recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee strictly adhere with all provisions of law, rules and regulations pertaining to procurements to protect at all times the interest of the local government unit and also to avoid legal problems in the future.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that –
The APP be submitted to the GPPB on or before the end of January of the budget year and be posted in accordance with E.O. 662, series of 2007, as amended;
At least one (1) observer from a duly recognized private group in a sector or discipline relevant to the procurement at hand, for example, national associations of contractors duly recognized by the Construction Industry Authority of the Philippines (CIAP) be invited in all stages of the procurement to enhance transparency;
