Recommendation/s:

We have recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee, who has the responsibility for ensuring that the procuring entity abides by the standards set forth by RA 9184 and its IRR, strictly adhere with all provisions of laws, rules and regulations pertaining to procurements to protect at all times the interest of the local government unit. We have further recommended that:

 An Annual Procurement Plan (APP) for infrastructure projects be prepared  in order to have basis in determining the quantity and quality of construction materials to be procured and ensure that procurements will be made in a manner beneficial to the financial interest of the local government unit;

Necessary warranty security be posted in accordance with Section 62 of RA 9184 and its IRR for projects funded by the National Government and implemented by the Local Government Unit by Administration;

The Notices of Award and Notices to Proceed and the approved contract of projects awarded be posted in the agency website;

The procedural guidelines under GPPB Resolution No. 09-2009 dated November 23, 2009 be observed in all procurements through shopping and small-value procurement to ensure that prices obtained are advantageous to the local government unit;

Observer from duly recognized private group be invited in all stages of procurement, for example in the procurement of goods, a specific relevant chamber-member of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry;

The maximum periods and the recommended earliest possible time for action on specific procurement activities as provided in Section 38.2 and Annex “C” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 be strictly observed; and

Advertise all Invitations to Bid for contracts under competitive bidding in such manner and for such length of time provided in Section 21.2 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act No. 9184 to ensure the widest possible dissemination of the procurement.

We have recommended that management be more cautious in the implementation of infrastructure projects and strictly comply with the submission of documentary requirements in compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations to protect the interest of the local government unit at all times. For the foregoing deficiencies, we have further recommended that:
The concerned officials and employees submit the supporting documents being required in the Concreting of FMR in Barangay San Blas – Caramutan and Barangay Barraca for further evaluation of the Audit Team and in order to avoid suspension or disallowance in audit.
Immediate repair be undertaken on the severe cracks noted in the stretch of the PCCP to avoid further damage on the newly rehabilitated road in Barangay Lapaz;
A copy of approved variation order be submitted to support the installation of additional RC pipes in the concreting of Calisan Road;
Relevant information be posted on signboards to inform the public of the essential features/elements of the infrastructure projects undertaken, encourage public participation and secure the right of the people to information on matters of public concern; and
The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer ensure the completeness of supporting documents before affixing their signatures in the disbursement vouchers and before effecting payments pursuant to Section 4 (6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445.

We have recommended that the Bids and Awards Committee, who has the responsibility for ensuring that the procuring entity abides by the standards set forth by RA 9184 and its IRR, strictly adhere with all provisions of laws, rules and regulations pertaining to procurements to protect at all times the interest of the local government unit. We have further recommended that:
An Annual Procurement Plan (APP) for infrastructure projects be prepared  in order to have basis in determining the quantity and quality of construction materials to be procured and ensure that procurements will be made in a manner beneficial to the financial interest of the local government unit;
Necessary warranty security be posted in accordance with Section 62 of RA 9184 and its IRR for projects funded by the National Government and implemented by the Local Government Unit by Administration;
The Notices of Award and Notices to Proceed and the approved contract of projects awarded be posted in the agency website;
The procedural guidelines under GPPB Resolution No. 09-2009 dated November 23, 2009 be observed in all procurements through shopping and small-value procurement to ensure that prices obtained are advantageous to the local government unit;
Observer from duly recognized private group be invited in all stages of procurement, for example in the procurement of goods, a specific relevant chamber-member of the Philippine Chamber of Commerce and Industry;
The maximum periods and the recommended earliest possible time for action on specific procurement activities as provided in Section 38.2 and Annex “C” of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184 be strictly observed; and
Advertise all Invitations to Bid for contracts under competitive bidding in such manner and for such length of time provided in Section 21.2 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act No. 9184 to ensure the widest possible dissemination of the procurement.

Recommendation/s:

We have recommended that the local government unit ensure management and accounting of its properties by observing the procedures provided by existing rules and regulations in the custody and management of properties specifically:

Keeping of Property Cards per category of Property, Plant and Equipment by the General Services Officer, Supply Officer or the Local Treasurer, as the case maybe;

Maintaining Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets and Real Property Ledger Cards for land by the Municipal Accountant;

Conducting annual physical inventory of all supplies or property of the local government unit as of December 31 of each year and submission of the report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the auditor concerned not later than January 31 of each year.

Reconciling the balance of the Property, Plant and Equipment with property card, ledger cards and RPCPPE.
